{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_dagger_ver01/data/sn96090259/00415623227/1913121901/0826.xml":{"full_text":"3\nr, .4\n1 I\n-f'\n.u\n4\na'\n?t\nV^'\nA\nJr*\n.5\n-1 xi\n,\"iJ\nV'\nfEfftr\ni,-,\u00a5\nTHIRTY-8EVEN MEN LOSE LIVES\nIN A MINE AT NEWCAS\nTLE, COLO.\nONLY THREE ESCAPE DEATH\nForeman L. L. Crawford and Fire Boss\nWalters Among Those Perishing\u2014\nTwenty-One Mangled and Burned\nBodies Recovered.\nNewcastle, Colo.\u2014Twonty-ono man\ngled and burned bodies of the thirty\nKovcn minors entombed in Hie Vulcan\nmine ol' the Kooky Mountain Fuel com\npany, when an explosion wrecked that,\nproperty, had been recovered by res\ncue crews and tlie helmet men report\ned the locations ol live more (lead\nminers. There was no hope that any\nof the thirty-seven miners was alive.\nOne of the pathetic incidents of res\nnio work was when Harry Meese, a\nstripling, emerged from the manway\ncarrying, unaided, the body of his dead\nfather, William.\nThat, so few miners were caught in\nthe explosion was due to the strike of\ncoal miners. Thirty Italian miners\nwere on strike and were living at\nNewcastle. When word of the serious\nexplosion reached them they hurried\nto the mine and joined the rescue\ncrews.\nThe cause of the explosion remains\nnnknown, but It was conjectured that\nthe explosion had been caused by a\nsudden accumulation of gas which an\nunprotected light, had ignited.\nNO CLEW TO MOB MEMBERS.\nMen Who Lynched Culbertson Are\nUnknown.\nWllliston, N. D.\u2014Williams county\nofficials began a thorough investiga\ntion of the lynching of Clove Culbert\nson, convicted murderer of T. Dillon,\nhis wife and daughter nt the Dillon\nfarm near Ray, last October. A cor\noner's jury returned a verdict to the\ncffect that it was impossible to name\nany of the members of the mob who\nentered the jail by battering down the\ndoor and later lianged Culbertson\nfrom a bridge over the Little Muddy\nriver a mile and a half from here.\nState's Attorney Burdlck and Sher\niff Erlckson admitted they had no clew\ntp the Identity of the members of the\nmob.\n8alvatlon Army Man Wanted.\nCincinnati, O.\u2014Satisfied there wore\nno more bodies in tbe ruins of tVe\n8alvatlon Army Industrial home, wh^c)i\n-was swept by Are, firemen and police\nceased to burrow into the tangled\nmass of debris in the basement of the\nbuilding. Five are kjiown to be dead,\nsixteen were more or less seriously\ninjured find ten more are still unac\ncounted for. A warrant was sworn\nout by District Fire Marshal George\nH. Coleman for the arrest of Maj. J.\nLi. Sprake, of the Salvation army, In\ncharge of the building, charging him\nwith violating the building regulations\nof Cincinnati. i\u2022?:&:\nKilled In Auto Wreck. -A\" if\nCharter Oak, la.\u2014Dr. A. B. Crewd\nson, a young veterinarian, was killed\nin an auto wreck near here. He and\nN. C. Hanson, a friend, had made a\nprofessional call in the country, and\nwere -returning when the automobile\nturned over. Mr. Hanson was slight\nly injured.\nCars Jump Track.\nJohnstown, Pa.\u2014Five men were se\nriously burned when a hot metal\ntrain was wrecked at the Cambric\nSteel works. The train, made up of\nalx ladle cars, each carrying fifteen\ntons of molten' metal, was speeding\nto the Franklin plant when two cars\nleft the track and toppled over Into\nthe Conemaugh river.\nMust Remain In Bed.\nMinneapolis, Minn.\u2014President M. E.\nCantlllon, of the Minneapolis Ameri\ncan Association Baseball club, report\ned 111, Is suffering from ulcers of the\nstomach, according to his physician.\n'Mr. Cantlllon has been ordered to re\nmain In bed for two weeks.\nPackages Rifled by Burglar*.\nWallace, Idaho.\u2014Three packages of\nregistered mall, containing $5,000 each\n\u2022nd aBout $2,000 In postofflce funds\n.were stolen from the safe of the local\npostofflce by burgiars. No trace of\nthem has yet been discovered.\nTray of Diamonds Selzad.\nKansas City, Mo.\u2014Robbers seised\na tray of diamonds worth $2,000 from\nthe store of L. Goldman, a diamond\nbroker in the business district, and\n\u2022scaped in an automobile.\nFlames Sweep Town.\nLynchburg, Va.\u2014Fire In tbe bust\ndistrict did $60,000 damage. The\ntflaqips started from an unknown cause.\nFlreln Salvation Army Home.\nCincinnati, O.\u2014Six are known to be\ntfead. one woman and two children are\nMissing and are thought to have per\nished and one was fatally injured in\nA lire which swept tbe 8alvatlon Army\nfcome for men on Freeman avenue.\ni,\nPartner of -Morgan.\n..New York.\u2014George 8. Bowdln. one\n\u00ab\u00abPW Hwtnerof the lateJ.P. Morgan,\ntftod-feero at Us hoaie in bis 82d year.\nBis aon T*mple is a member of tb*\nWEEKS\nN E W S\nSummarized for\nVery Busy Readers\nWashington\nSenator Elihu Root of New York se\nvuioly arraigned the administration\ncurrency bill in the senate at Wash\ningtou,\nRepresentative Harrison of Missis\nsippi has prepared a bill, which he\nwill Introduce in the house at Wash\nIngton, to declare illegal options and\nfutures on cotton, hops, wheat, corn,\noat\u00ab, rye, barley, wheat flour, pork,\nlard, bacon or other agricultural or\nfood products.\nAndrew Carnegie takes little stock\nin rumors of business depression,\neither present or impending. At th'j\nWhite House in Washington when\nasked what he thought of the general\nbusiness outlook, Mr. Carnegie said:\n\"The recent reports of impending\nwidespread business depression arfl\nall tommyrot\" I\nThe administration currency bill\nwas subjected to many attacks dur\ning the debate in the senate at Wash\nington.\nA sweeping investigation of transit\nrates on live stock over railroads in\nwestern classification territory was\nordered by the interstate commerce\ncommission at Washington. isi's-a\ns~\nMountain Laurel is proposed as the\nofficial national flower of the United\nStates In a bill Introduced in the\nhouse at \"Washington by Representa\ntive Kinkead of New York.\nPresident Wilson has taken more\ncold and canceled afl his engagements\nby order of his physician. Chief Jus\ntice White and Justice L.urton also are\nconfined to their homes in Washington\nsuffering with colds.\nDomestic.\n1\nThe house at Washington was turned\ninto a circus for an hour and a balf.\nItepresentatives Hobson and Bartholdt\ndebated the prohibition question be-\"\nfore crowded galleries. Underwood\nrose repeatedly to charge Mr. Hobson\nwith misrepresenting him.\nGovernment ownership of telegraph\nand telephone lines is being serious\nly considered by the president. Con\nferences between the president and\nPostmaster General Burleson at Wash\nington have led to a gathering of in\nformation about the practical work\nings of government ownership in other\ncountries.\nSecretary of War Garrison\" in his\nannual report said the time had not\nyet come for disarming or slackening\nthe* nation's efforts for preparedness\nIn case of war. He also declared the\npresent provision for an army reserve\nis not working satisfactorily.\nGovernor Major of Missouri told the\nhouse roads committee at Washington\nthat be favored the federal govern\nment's rental of post roads in agricul\ntural communities and that the lowest\nrental proposed in the pending Shack\nleford bill would be sufficient to main\ntain such roads.\nThe first conviction under a* new\nstate law concerning fraudulent adver\ntising of merchandise was obtained'\nwhen William H. Meloney of Hartford,\nConn., was fined $20. He advertised a\nsale of second-hand goods at his home.\nThe complainant testified to buying for\n$20 a rug advertised to be worth $65,\nand which later was found to have\nbeen bought at a department store for\n$12.60.\nThe revenue cutter Windom is be\ning rushed to Velasco, the town near\nest the Inundated section in Texas.\nHarry A. Black, chairman of the Gal\nveston relief committee, telegraphed\nBecretaryj McAdoo at Washington that\ntwo counties are almost entirely under\nwater.\ni*\n\"We are clearly of the opinion that\nthere should be a substantial advance\nnow, provided that such additional rev\nenue can be obtained without imposing\nupon the publlo unjust and unreason\nable transportation charges,\" says the\nconference of railroad commissioners\nIn Its report upon the proposition of\nthe Boston Maine railroad to in\ncrease its rates.\nThree persona were murdered and\ntwo seriously wounded In Chicago\nwithin twenty-fpur hours. Jealousy\nand marital troubles were responsible\nfor tbe murder of three persons, tbe\nself-destruction of their assailants, and\ntbe serious injury of two others.\nJoseph Anderson was shot and\nkilled by Mamie Ltndsey at Lan\ncaster, Pa. It Is said that tbe dead\nman was Jealous of bis son. who\nhad eclipsed bin In winning the af\nfections of the woman. She was ar\nrested.\nA bomb delivered in tbe office of\nthe O. K. Bottling company,\nv^\nv,\n,7-\n\u2022f\" 1\nOne hundred guests narrowly es\u00adt\ncaped incineration and more than\n$125,000 damage was caused by a lire\nwhich destroyed the Astoria hoU'l at\nChaffee, Mo.\n\u2022vv.V.:\u00a5\nFire destroyed the warehouse of thr\nIllinois Warehouse company at Pi oria,\n111., causing a loss estimated at\n000.\nv, if V.\nThe coroner of Philadelphia\nCharges that the American Tele\nphone and Telegraph company, tho\nCentral Union Telephone company and\ntho Chicago Telephone company con\nspired to wreck the Interstate com\npany and drive it from the competing\nfield in Illinois, were made in a bill\nfiled In the circuit court on behalf of\n78 bondholders of the Interstate com:\npany.\nAfter an all-night search Sheriff\nRussell captured three\nMexican Revolt\nForeign\n628-630\nWest Thirty-eighth street. New York,\nexploded and killed an eighteen-year\nold girl. Id* Anusewlts. Thomas Mfr\nCabe, the office fcianager. was fatally\nhurt\nBuspects\n\"T*~\nHOT 8PRING8 WEEKLY STAR HOT SPRINGS, SOUTH DAKOTA.\nWhat is eaid to be the finest known\nblue-white diamond in the world was\non exhibition in a Jeweler's showroom\nin Fifth avenue, New York. It is worth\n$300,000. The stone was discovered re\ncently in Africa. It weighs 150 carats,\nand is said to be absolutely free fro\u2122\nImperfections.\nUik\nposed of an unusual medical case '.vlicn\na jury rendered a verdict that Norman\nB. Musselman, twenty-one yearB old,\nhad died of horse asthma complicated\nwith an injection of diphtheritic anti\ntoxin. \"It is impossible for a person\nsuffering from it to be near a horse\nwithout strangling or feeling ill,\" the\ncoroner's physician said.\nWith Its starboard main-shaft pro\npeller broken and seweral of its com\npartments flooded, the battleship Ver\nmont is on its way toward Hampton\nroads on the return trip from the\nMediterranean cruise. It Is under\nconvoy of the battleship Delaware and\nthe colliers Orion and Jason.\nThe Harvard seniors at Cambridge,\nMass., have elected a negro, Alexan\nder L. Jackeon of Englewood, N. J,\ntheir orator for class day, 1914.\nThe motorcycle corps of the New\nYork police department of 23 men has\narrested more than 13,000 persons in\nthe last year. The total of fines Im\nposed has been over $117,000.\nPere Marquette railroad was fined\n$6,100 and the Wabash assessed $400\nby Judge Arthur J. Tuttel in the United\n(States court at Detroit, Mich., the for\nmer for failure to obey In full the fed\neral railroad laws, and the latter for\nthe violation, of the safety appliance\nlaw.\nfor\nsafe blowing at Lawler, la. The men\nhad $160 in money, many gold rings\nand,a complete outfi\u00a3 of burglar tools\nAmericans, Germans and Spaniards,\nwho arrived at El Paso, Tex., from\nChihuahua, Mexico, report that Fran\ncisco Villa, the rebel leader, virtually\nhad constituted himself dictator there\nand that he refused to heed the re\nquests of representatives of foreign\ngovernments. Villa sent word to the\nfederal commander, who had retaken\nTorreon, that if he marched on Chihua\nhua, Luis Terrazas, Jr., son of Gen.\nLuis Terrazas, the wealthiest native In\nMexico, would be executed.\nTwenty women and children were\nInjured in London in a riot growing\nout of an attempt by the police to dis\nperse a procession of suffragettes In\nthe Bow street district.\n\"Mona Lisa,\" Leonardo da Vinci's\nmasterpiece, the mysterious disap\npearance of which from the Louvre\nin August. 1911, threw the art world\nInto consternation, was found in Flor\nence, Italy. The man who stole It was\narrested.\nv. .-\"v\nGreat excitement was caused on the\nbourse at Madrid, Spain, by the fail\nure of the .Banko Hispano-Amerlcano,\na $20,000,000 Institution, to open its\ndoors.\nMiss Helen Ooudy of Chicago/noted\nbeauty of the American 1 colony, be\ncame tbe bride of Lieut Gerard Leigh\nof tbe Vlrst Life guards. The wed\nding took place In St George's Han\nover square, London.\nThe Russian government proposed\ntbe withdrawal of all foreign troops\nfrom Peking and the entire province\nof Chl-Ll, China, including the lega\ntion guards, tho regiments at Tientsin\nand tho troops guarding tho railway\nbetween tbe sea and Peklfag. Russia\nconsiders, conditions In the north of\nChina no' longer dangerous to foreign\ners.\nmk\nRead Admiral Fletcher, commander\nof the American naval forces in Mex\nican waters, ordered the rebels and\nfederals fighting at Tampico to cease\nfiring, threatening to open upon them\nwith the guns of the gunboat Wheel\ning if his order was not obey. Both\nsides obeyed.\nt\\\nv,s\nAmericans who arrived at El Paso,\nTex., from Chihuahua reported that\nBince their occupation of that city the\nrebels had entered the British vice\nconsulate and forcibly seized Luie Ter\nrazas, Jr., a son of the wealthiest land\nowner In Mexico and placed him In\nJail.\n\nN\nJohn Holloway, vice-chairman of\nthe port docks board, was shot during\nft, ridt between nonunion coal men and\nstrikers at Dahlia\nDITCH PLANS READY\nLITTELL SNIVELY HAS REPORT\nOF CHEYENNE RIVER PROJ\nECT SURVEY READY.\nHAPPENINGS 0VERTHESTATE\nWhat is Going on Here and There\nThat is of Interest to the Read-\n4\ners Throughout South Da\nkota and Vicinity.\nHot Springs.\u2014Littell Snively, con\nsulting engineer of the Big Cheyenne\nriver irrigation project in this\ncounty,\nlias returned from Pierre, where he\nhas been connected with the state en\nginner's office in getting out his re\nport of the survey which was com\npleted about a month ago. The state\nengineer is now busily engaged in\ngetting up a prospectus of the entire\nproject, which' will be nicely illus\ntrated, showing ranch scenes and the\ncharacter of the lands which come\nunder the ditch. This report is made\nunder the authority of the state, and\nwill be presented to the government\nthrough South Dakota's representation\nin congress, and it is expected that\nthe government will acoept the proj\nect and make an appropriation for It\nat once, bringing these lands under\nirrigation. The state engineers,\nthrough the work of Mr. Snively,\nhave become very enthusiastic over\nthis project and pronounce it one of\nthe finest in the west, which means a\ngreat deal, for Mr. Shively has had\nexperience and is familiar with many\nof the government projects. He pro\nnounces these lands superior to any\nthat have yet been undertaken, which,\nwith a superior and attractive climate,\nmakes it a decidedly attractive propo\nI sition, not only for the government to\nI place under irrigation, but for pros\npective land purchasers.\nI It is the plan under this project to\nhave two large ditches leading from\nan immense reservoir in the Cheyenne\nriver. The height of the dam will be\n156 feet, and its width at the base\nabout 200 feet and at the top 970\nfeet. It will hold 164,965-acre feet of\nwater, or sufficient to irrigate the 90,\n000 acres that will come under the\nditch to a depth of two feet each sea\nson. The estimated cost of, the project\nis $35.50 per acre\u2014which includes all\nlaterals to lands and everything to\ncomplete the thorough irrigation of a\nlittle over 90,000 acres. This estimate\nis based upon government cost, which\nIs said to be much greater than where\nIt Is done by private contract. Yet\nthis estimate, which the engineers\nhave been generous In figuring, is\nconsiderably less per acre than a large\nnumber of projects that the govern\nment has thus far undertaken. Nearly\nall of the land under this project is\nalready deeded, but the owners will\nbe very glad to pay the amount of the\nestimate for Irrigation, and in fact\nwould willingly pay a greater sum if\nnecessary, for they easily estimate\nthat their land would at once be worth\nfrom $75 to $100 an acre as soon as It\nIs irrigated.\nAn idea of the capacity of thfe res\nervoir may be gained when it is\nknown that It will be ninety miles\naround it when filled with water. It\nwill make one of the most beautiful\nlakes In the country, as the surround\ning reg'on is most picturesque, lying\njust at the foot of the Black Hills,\nwith scattering pines and cedar and\nrugged rock cliffs. J. G. Keith, a resi\ndent of Cascade Springs, which will\nborder this reservoir, is so impressed\nwith the attractiveness of this reser\nvoir (lake) that he has proposed to\nthe government that he will give $100,\n000 for a concession of the reservoir\nfor the use of boats and all Its fishing\nand hunting privileges. Mr. Keith\nknows something about catering to\nthe tastes of the traveling and sight\nseeing public, for he had a miniature\n\"wind cave\" at the world's fair at\nChicago and afterwards moved it to\nthe Paris exposition\u2014attracting thou\nsands of visitors every day throughout\nthose great expositions.\nThis reservoir will be about ten\nmiles from Hot Springs, while a large\nportion of the lands are nearer by, be\ning within seven miles of this place.\nAlready land owners are beginning to\ntalk about land values, although they\nseem yet to be holding their heads\nsteady and are generally not speculat\ning on future values to airy extent,\neven though an occasional owner who\nwas most anxious a few months ago\nto dispose of his holdings, now de\nclare that their land Is not for sale.\nBut when It Is considered that It will\n\"take a few years at least before this\nproject can be completed the poor\nranchers who have suffered the effect\nof a couple of seasons of drought take\na second thought and declare that\nthey would willingly share their hold\nings with land speculators. Thus has\nthis new enterprise created a hope and\nconfidence that Is already Inspiring.\nGun Shot Wound Fatal.\nPierre.\u2014Henry Russell, a farmer in\neastern Sully county, diod at Onlda\nfrom the results of a gunshot wound\ncaused by pulling a loaded gun from\nhis wagon. The charge so badly shat\nered a leg that amputation did not\nsave his life.\nWithin four days after the attempted\ncrime, William Sayles of Mitchell, who\nattempted a statutory crime agalnBt\nMrs. Louise Groeber, was found guilty\nof tho offense by a Davison county\n!*ry.\nSHOW FOR ABERDEEN.\nFarm Products Exposition to Be H\u00abld\nNext Fall.\nAberdeen.\u2014The Aberdeen Commer\ncial club will hold a \"Farm Products\nFJxposition\" in Aberdeen the lattei\npart of September or the first part ol\nOctober, at which $1,000 in cash prizes\nwill be given to the farmers for the\nbest exhibits of small grains, corn,\nalfalfa, cows, horses, swine and poul\ntry. An additional $1,000 will be ex\npended lor entertainment and in se\ncuring the services of competent\njudges and speakers for the occasion.\nlTnl!ke ordinary lairs ot this nature,\ntin' excellence ot the sample exhibited\nwill bo only one ol the iniiioi points\nin the awarding of the prizes. All\ngrain exhibits must be made on tho\nbasis 01 50 per cent for yield. 25 per\ncent for cost of production and 25 per\ncent lor samples shown.\nPotatoes and alfalfa, awards will be\nmade trom five-acre plots on the same\nbasis of awards. Stock to be entered\nin this contest must be bred from\npure blooded sires.\nTime for Examination Set.\nMarvin.\u2014December 29 has been\nfixed as the time lor the preliminary\nexamination of Fred Joranger, who\nrecently was arrested on the charge\nof embezzlement, complaint in the\ncase being made by a bonding com\npany which had furnished him a bond\nas manager of the branch yard in\nMarvin of the McGowan Lumber com\npany. It is believed that he was short\nin his accounts with the lumber com\npany to the amount of about $3000.\nHis alleged shortage is said to be duo\npurely to poor business management\nand not to any desire or intention 011\nhis part to wrongfully convert tho\nmoney to his own use. It is stated\nthat his relatives in Minnesota have\nrallied to his aid, and a settlement\nmay be made with the bonding com\npany and the lumber company befora\nthe date fixed for his preliminary\nhearing. Mr. Joranger also conducted\na furniture store, and is the owner of\nlots in Marvin, Summit and Twin\nBrooks.\nRefuse to Give Information.\nWoonsocket.\u2014The fact that several\nboy pupils of the public schools have\nrecently been found in an intoxicated\ncondition has caused a sensation here\nand efforts have, been made by tho\nauthorities to apprehend the men who\nare supposed to have furnished the\nboys liquor. Several arrests were\nmade, but the justice before whom the\npreliminary hearing of the defendants\nwas held deemed the evidence intro\nduced insufficient and declined to hold\nthe defendants for trial in the stata\ncircuit court. One of the cases was\ndismissed following the refusal of a\nwitness to answer questions in refer\nence as to where he had secured\nliquor. Some friction ensued between\nthe state's attorney and the justice,\nthe state's attorney maintaining that\nthe justice should have held the wit\nness under a contempt charge when\nhe refused to answer the question of\nthe prosecution. a\nSeeking Radium Supply.\nDeadwood.\u2014J. W. Young, a mining\nexpert of Salt Lake City, is here in\nvestigating sources of radium produc\ntion in the interests of a Pittsburgh\nchemical concern. He made a trip to\ntie up-gulch country, company with\nJohn Treber and went over the\nground which was formerly owned by\nthe late Baron Dafier and is now\namong the holdings by the New Be\nliance Mining company. On the\nground there is exposed a 40-foot ver\u00bb\ntical vein of uranium bearing rock\nwhich is heavily impregnated with\nthe yellow stain of that mineral. Sam\nples ^ere brought to Deadwood and\nwill be subjected to tests by the peo\nple whom Mr. Young represents here.\nIf the ore is found to be sufficiently\nrich in the rare mineral, it is the in\ntention to mine It on an extensive\nscale and probably erect a concentrat\ning plant at or near the property.\nFarmers' Convention.\nBrookings.\u2014\"It is essentially a two\nweeks' convention of studious farm\ners,\" says Dr. A. N. Hume, of the\nfarmers' short course In agriculture\nwhich will convene at the State col\nlege for two weeks, beginning Janu\nary 6. \"It is a sufficient time for get\nting acquainted with other influential\npeople of the same calling, and suf\nficient for hearing a number of talks\n\u2014illustrated and otherwise\u2014concern\ning the outstanding problems of South\nDakota agriculture.\" Dr. Hume sug\ngests that farmers should bring their\nown problems with them for discus\nsion with the professors and other\nfarmers. There were more than 100\nenrolled last year in the short courses.\nThe college has free illustrated bub\nletlns describing the course.\nSerious Accident at Canton.\nCanton.\u2014Gunder Tvedt, a Lincoln\ncounty pioneer, was seriously Injured\nwhen his team became frightened at\na passing automobile, ran away and\nthrew him out of the carriage. Two\nribs were broken and he suffered in?\nteraal Injuries.\nBond Election Wanted.\nBonesteel.\u2014A petition signed by\nmore than 75 per cent of the voters\nof the district has been filed with the\nschool board requesting them to call\na special election to vote bonds for\nthe erection of a new school building\nIn Bonesteel. The new building will\ncost in the neighborhood of $20,000\nand no opposition to the movement 1s\nanticipated. It is planned to com\nmence the building In the early spring\nand have it completed in time for thr\nfall torn.\nA\na\n*7 v\\\nSSii.- 'ivliaJW\nNEWS OF BOOTH DAKOTA.\nA. C. Brink, a leading business man\nor Pierre, is suffering from a paralytic\nstroke.\nA. J. Garner, a Madison contractor,,\nwas seriously injured in a fall from iv\nbuile ng on which he was working:\nat Piankinton.\nMiss ICduh, Strever lias assumed'\nthe duties of postmistress at Ham mil.\nUntil recently she was teacher of as.\ncountry school near town.\nJohn Wilkes, of Spearfish, pleaded\nguilty o* theft when confronted with,\nevidence ol a trail of flour Irom tlie\nwarehouse 10 his own door.\nPaul Hempel, of Parkston, has a.\ndream of a trolley driven carrier tc\ntake the place of the rural mail ear\nlier, 1\nlie carrier to travel 011 the\nroadsifle fence.\nGeorge Johnson, of Egan, committed\nsuicide in an old house near the rail\nroad junction south of Egan. It is\nthought tluit he shot himself because\not disappointment in love.\nThe state's financial report for No\nvember, shows $523,793 in cash, $68,\n968 ol which is in general fund, $49,\n330 in game fund, $177,685 in schooTl\nfund which is to be distributed this\nmonth, $170,211 in twine plant fund.\nFarmers in the vicinity of Valley, in.\nHyde county, are planning a rabbit\ndrive some time in the near future\nRabbits are unusually thick this year\nand it is planned to organize twc\u00bb\nsides and stage a competitive drive.\nHarold Conklin, aged 22, son of a\nwell known Kingsbury county farmer,.,\ndied from injuries received when a.\npart of a corn shelling machine he\nwas assisting in operating broke loose\nand struck him a terrible blow. He\nlived only ten minutes after being.\nstruck.\nAn uncancelled check, has been?\nfound in Sioux Falls, drawn April 18,...\n1SS5, pavablo to A. Johnson, by Arth\nur Johnson of that city. The check\nwas made out by D. W. Stites, at the-'\ntime deputy treasurer of Minnehaha\ncounty. It has never passed through\nthe clearing house.\nA peculiar case is reported from\nVendori township, near Pukwana,.\nwhere Alois Kepola, a well known,\nfarmer, beciwue insane as the result\nof lead poisoning. His condition was*:\nlound so serious that it will be neces\nsary to send him to the state hospital:\nfor the insane at Yankton.\nIn the belief that a \"firebug\" may\nhave been operating at Platte, Insur\nance Commissioner St.ablen and a dep\nuty have been there investigating a re\u2014\ncent fire which destroyed the Roger\nhouse in Castalia township. The of- 1\nfleers would not discuss the nature of\"\nthe evidence which they had secured.\nE. A. Paulson, buttermaker at the\nWebster Co-Operative creamery, has:\nreceived a silver cup, gold-lined, re\ncently awarded liim by the National:\nCreamery Butte: makers' association\nfor having on exhibition at the recent\nbutter show in Chicago, the highest,\ntest butter exliihi'ed frcni South Da\nkota.\nWhile driving in their automobile,.\nG. H. Getman and family, of Mcln-\ntosh were all painfully injured and the\nautomobile was rendered a total wreck\nas it dashed over a steep cnbankment\non the old Wade trail near Mcintosh..\nThe machine dropped a distance of 10*\nfeet while going at a good rate of\"\nspeed.\nRev. E. F. Tilley, for the past three\nyears pastor of the First Baptist\nchurch of Mitchell, has offered his\nresignation, to take effect March 1\u201e\n1914. In the time that Rev. Mr. Til\nley has occupied the Mitchell pulpit\nhe has doubled the membership of the\nchurch and built a new stone struc\nture. Completion of his mission in\nMitchell is given as the reason for\nthe resignation.\nThrough a local item in the Ortley\nOutlook, F. M. Pearson, a traveling:\n\"medicine man\" known as \"Dr. Bliss,\"\nfound his son from whom he had been\nseparated for many years. The son, a\nwell-to-do slock buyer at Sacred Heart.,\nMinn., happened to pick up a copy otr\nthe Outlook at a botel and Saw a men\ntion of his father. He communicated^\nwith \"Dr. Bliss,\" and a reunion of fa\nther and son followed.\nPerkins county nimrods matched?\nskill recently with the hunters of Cor\nson county, in a rabbit hunting con\ntest. When the count was made at\nthe close of a day of heroic cndeavoi?*\nthere was found to be a grand total'\nof 600 jackrabblts, making two double\nwagon box loads. The average kiln\nper man from Corson county exeeded*\nthat of the Perkins county sportsmen'\nand the latter paid for an oyster sup\nper and a dance.\nAndrew Marsh, of Vanderbilt, a pio\nneer of the Dakota territory dating?\nback to the time of the civil war, died!1\nat Aberdeen from the complications*\nresulting from several years' sickness.\nMarsh came to Dakota driving a herd!\nof cattle for the use of the soldiers^\nat Fort Lincoln. He was then various\nly engaged at wood cutting, stock raid\ning and prospecting along the Mir\nsouri river and in the Black Hill untlH\nbe retired eight years ago.\nThe arrival at Winner of a number\nof officials of the Northwestern Rail\nroad company, and their inspection of\nthe region west of Winner, has given*\nrise to the rumor that the company\ncontemplates an early extension to\nCarter and points In Mellette county-\nRev. G. Ifi Peacock, for some time\npastor of the Cottonwood Congrega\ntional church, has accepted a call to\nthe pastorate of the Congregational^\nchurch at Cass Lake and Wymore^\nMlno. lie expects to assume his new\nluli'js there the first Sunday in Ja\u00bb\nJii r.\n1\n1\n-?,x.\n1\nA\ni'\u00a3\nj,","height":"29860","width":"20940"}}
